snippet: We deep forest crowded Australian paperback trees, air thick humidity eerily silent save screeching tropical birds, <PERSON>Marcus</PERSON> shouts: Look, crocodiles!    As <ORGANIZATION>Reuters</ORGANIZATION> photojournalist, I'm trained...
lead_paragraph: We are deep in a forest crowded by Australian paperback trees, the air thick with humidity but eerily silent save for the screeching of tropical birds, when <PERSON>Marcus</PERSON> shouts: Look, crocodiles!    As a <ORGANIZATION>Reuters</ORGANIZATION> photojournalist, I'm a trained observer, but I can't see any crocs. I can't see anything beyond mud and what little water is left in the small billabong.    Aboriginal hunters <PERSON>Marcus and Roy</PERSON>, a father and son team, take off running past a herd of water buffalo and by the time I catch up <PERSON>Roy</PERSON> is standing ankle-deep in murky water, his shotgun pointed at the surface.    Hang on a minute: wasn't your son pointing at crocodiles in that water ten seconds ago? Is this safe?
headline: {main:Hunting Pictures, Crocodiles, Remote Aboriginal Country,print_headline:Hunting Pictures, Crocodiles, Remote Aboriginal Country}
